718
00:53:18,929 --> 00:53:22,558
Egad, this place looks
like a funeral parlour.

719
00:53:22,729 --> 00:53:24,799
Nobody cares if roses give
me hay fever.

720
00:53:24,969 --> 00:53:27,278
- Where are your shoes?
- In the dressing room!

721
00:53:27,449 --> 00:53:29,360
- Get them!
- I can't! The dressing room...

722
00:53:29,529 --> 00:53:32,043
...is full of photographers taking
pictures of the mirror!

723
00:53:32,209 --> 00:53:33,278
For Pete's sake, why?

724
00:53:33,449 --> 00:53:38,603
It's gonna be in the Sunday paper. The
mirror where Rusty first saw her face.

725
00:53:39,449 --> 00:53:41,724
- Mr. McGuire.
- I know. Do the best you can.

726
00:53:41,889 --> 00:53:44,562
That newspaperwoman is eating
my precious food.

727
00:53:44,729 --> 00:53:47,960
She is doing a story on what food
makes the figure of Rusty Parker.

728
00:53:48,129 --> 00:53:50,085
- I said, do the best you can.
- I quit.

729
00:53:50,249 --> 00:53:52,240
All right, then quit!

730
00:53:52,449 --> 00:53:53,438
- Genius.
- Yes.

731
00:53:53,609 --> 00:53:55,486
- Where is Rusty? Find her.
- Relax.

732
00:53:55,649 --> 00:53:58,641
She's all right. She's on the stage
being interviewed.

733
00:54:00,729 --> 00:54:03,482
- I'm 10 minutes slow.
- Are the flowers from Mr. Wheaton?

734
00:54:03,649 --> 00:54:05,879
Yes, every hour, on the hour,
for a week.

735
00:54:06,049 --> 00:54:08,085
Can you tell us about their romance?

736
00:54:08,249 --> 00:54:10,285
Which of you did she love
before Mr. Wheaton?

737
00:54:10,449 --> 00:54:12,167
It was I, but I beat her.

738
00:54:12,329 --> 00:54:15,321
Mr. McGuire. Smile.

739
00:54:20,249 --> 00:54:22,365
- Where's Rusty?
- We want her autograph.

740
00:54:22,529 --> 00:54:24,679
Wait outside. We're trying to rehearse.

741
00:54:24,849 --> 00:54:27,886
- Give me your autograph.
- You don't even know who I am.

742
00:54:28,049 --> 00:54:29,038
Yes, I do.

743
00:54:29,209 --> 00:54:32,599
- You're Rusty Parker's boyfriend.
- I'll tell him when he comes.

744
00:54:32,809 --> 00:54:36,085
You can have my autograph.
Single file. I'll take you first.

745
00:54:36,249 --> 00:54:37,284
You ain't nobody.

746
00:54:37,449 --> 00:54:40,919
Maybe we can catch her
out in the alley. Come on!

747
00:54:42,649 --> 00:54:45,288
Just a minute. The girls
are too busy to see you.

748
00:54:45,449 --> 00:54:48,327
- Glad to see you.
- Glad to see you.

749
00:54:58,129 --> 00:55:01,519
That's fine, John. Play billiards
while my theatre falls apart.

750
00:55:01,689 --> 00:55:03,680
- Good afternoon.
- What's good about it?

751
00:55:03,849 --> 00:55:07,046
It's another day for me to worry about
how I'll open my show.

752
00:55:07,209 --> 00:55:10,167
Now I'm sending roses
every 15 minutes.

753
00:55:10,369 --> 00:55:14,885
You got me this way. Do something.
I tried everything this side of kidnapping.

754
00:55:15,089 --> 00:55:16,841
What is this side of kidnapping?

755
00:55:17,049 --> 00:55:18,960
Please don't be humorous.

756
00:55:19,169 --> 00:55:21,046
You're humorous, both of you.

757
00:55:21,209 --> 00:55:23,040
You're attempting the impossible:

758
00:55:23,209 --> 00:55:26,281
Lure a girl away from a guy
she loves with things.

759
00:55:26,449 --> 00:55:31,603
It won't work, and I'm dame enough to
be glad of it. What do you think of that?

760
00:55:31,769 --> 00:55:35,125
I had the same problem with her
grandmother. I mean, her mother.

761
00:55:35,409 --> 00:55:37,639
Whose mother?

762
00:55:39,529 --> 00:55:41,679
Nobody's, believe me.

763
00:55:41,849 --> 00:55:44,841
But it can be done.
I want that child on Broadway.

764
00:55:45,129 --> 00:55:46,881
Everything's set and ready to go.

765
00:55:47,049 --> 00:55:51,042
- Frame's built, and no face to go in it.
- You'll have the face. Let me work on it.

766
00:55:51,209 --> 00:55:53,165
Gladly, only work fast, will you? L...

767
00:55:53,329 --> 00:55:56,878
Immediately. Tomorrow night, in fact.
Keep the evening open.

768
00:55:57,049 --> 00:56:00,724
Enter the mastermind.

769
00:56:02,449 --> 00:56:05,247
Good afternoon, gentlemen.

770
00:56:11,329 --> 00:56:15,641
All is clear, master.
You may bring forth the treasure.

771
00:56:18,049 --> 00:56:22,088
No photographers, no adoring public.
Zounds, princess, you are slipping.

772
00:56:22,249 --> 00:56:26,083
- Listen to what I'm saying.
- You said Mr. Coudair was sentimental.

773
00:56:26,249 --> 00:56:29,161
I said he can be sentimental
on his own time. Then what?

774
00:56:29,329 --> 00:56:31,445
Look.

775
00:56:32,449 --> 00:56:34,599
- Genius, explain it to him.
- Mr. McGuire...

776
00:56:34,769 --> 00:56:39,604
You don't need to explain. You want
to skip the show and go to a party.

777
00:56:39,769 --> 00:56:40,758
The second show.

778
00:56:40,929 --> 00:56:43,602
It's an anniversary dinner
at Mr. Coudair's house.

779
00:56:43,769 --> 00:56:46,966
- Imagine, eating in a house.
- It's <i>Vanity</i>'s 50th birthday.

780
00:56:47,129 --> 00:56:49,563
Why waste good food
on an old hag like that?

781
00:56:49,729 --> 00:56:51,606
Will you please stop clowning?

782
00:56:51,769 --> 00:56:54,363
I'm the Golden Wedding Girl,
so he wants me there.

783
00:56:54,529 --> 00:56:58,158
And because you work
at Danny McGuire's, I want you there.

784
00:56:58,329 --> 00:57:00,285
Do you only think of what you want?

785
00:57:00,449 --> 00:57:02,758
Mr. Coudair has the right
to want something.

786
00:57:02,929 --> 00:57:06,922
Once won't hurt. The guy's sentimental.
It can't happen again for 50 years.

787
00:57:07,089 --> 00:57:10,286
You think he'd be sentimental
if she worked in Wheaton's show?

788
00:57:10,449 --> 00:57:12,883
He wouldn't. Why should he
kick our show around...

789
00:57:13,049 --> 00:57:16,166
...because it's Brooklyn?
- It's not kicking your show around...

790
00:57:16,329 --> 00:57:20,641
...that he's brought you more business
because of me than you've had before!

791
00:57:22,249 --> 00:57:24,205
I wondered when that was coming.

792
00:57:24,369 --> 00:57:28,647
That's what the ads read. " Come to
Danny McGuire's to see Rusty Parker."

793
00:57:28,809 --> 00:57:31,687
All the more reason you should
be there when they come.

794
00:57:31,849 --> 00:57:36,684
I'll be there, Danny, for the first show.
But after the first show, I'm leaving.

795
00:57:36,849 --> 00:57:39,841
And you can get mad if you want to.

796
00:57:42,529 --> 00:57:44,884
Oh, she's a great kid, always clowning.

797
00:57:45,049 --> 00:57:47,358
You don't think she'd really do that,
do you?

798
00:57:47,529 --> 00:57:49,247
Great sense of humour, that kid.

799
00:58:00,249 --> 00:58:04,367
Peace, it's wonderful.
What quieted all of you down?

800
00:58:07,249 --> 00:58:09,843
- Where's Rusty?
- She went to a party.

801
00:58:10,129 --> 00:58:12,245
You should've seen how swell
she looked.

802
00:58:12,449 --> 00:58:16,920
Just one word from you, and she does
what she likes, doesn't she, boss?

803
00:58:17,089 --> 00:58:18,966
- On stage.
- Just the six of us?

804
00:58:19,129 --> 00:58:21,040
Space it a little. You can cover it.

805
00:58:21,209 --> 00:58:23,165
We will, Danny.

806
00:58:26,529 --> 00:58:28,565
Yeah, great sense of humour, that kid.

807
00:58:28,729 --> 00:58:31,448
You know, Danny, the funniest thing
just happened.

808
00:58:31,609 --> 00:58:35,284
Coudair's more sentimental than
anybody I heard of. Did you know that?

809
00:58:35,449 --> 00:58:37,963
- Touching.
- He's even sentimental about us.

810
00:58:38,129 --> 00:58:41,963
Yeah, he just phoned. He wants you
to come to the party to pick Rusty up.

811
00:58:42,129 --> 00:58:45,678
Imagine that. A guy like him who's
got a barrelful of rubies...

812
00:58:45,849 --> 00:58:47,885
...and he's sentimental about a pearl.

813
00:58:48,049 --> 00:58:50,768
I guess he thinks it'd be nice
if we were friends.

814
00:58:50,929 --> 00:58:54,888
You have a great brain. Sometimes
it almost frightens me, you're so bright.

815
00:58:55,049 --> 00:58:57,882
You know, sometimes
it almost frightens me too.

816
00:58:58,049 --> 00:59:00,768
But you're going to the party,
aren't you, Danny?

817
00:59:00,929 --> 00:59:02,920
Sure.

818
00:59:03,449 --> 00:59:05,917
Sure, I'm going.

819
00:59:06,329 --> 00:59:08,638
I love parties.

820
00:59:18,649 --> 00:59:22,483
Here's the church, there's the steeple.
Open the door, and where's the people?

821
00:59:22,649 --> 00:59:23,684
I beg your pardon.

822
00:59:23,849 --> 00:59:26,488
Oh, a nursery rhyme.
I beg your pardon.

823
00:59:26,649 --> 00:59:28,765
Yes, sir. Will you come into the study?

824
00:59:28,929 --> 00:59:31,921
Mr. Coudair asked
that you be brought right in.

825
00:59:34,849 --> 00:59:38,524
- Nice to see you, Mr. McGuire.
- Nice to see you too, Mr. Coudair.

826
00:59:38,729 --> 00:59:40,367
I guess I'm a little mixed- up.

827
00:59:40,529 --> 00:59:42,679
Your message said Rusty'd be here.

828
00:59:42,849 --> 00:59:46,478
Yes, well, we changed plans
at the last minute, and we've...

829
00:59:46,649 --> 00:59:48,560
Won't you sit down and have a drink?

830
00:59:48,729 --> 00:59:50,720
Thanks.

831
00:59:51,929 --> 00:59:55,239
Where is Rusty, Mr. Coudair?

832
00:59:56,329 --> 00:59:58,365
I don't really know.

833
00:59:58,529 --> 01:00:02,841
She and Mr. Wheaton had some sort of
an evening figured out, I understand.

834
01:00:03,929 --> 01:00:06,887
This isn't the right direction
for Mr. Coudair's house.

835
01:00:07,049 --> 01:00:10,564
You're being kidnapped. You like it?

836
01:00:10,729 --> 01:00:13,368
You're not very complimentary.
You're not scared.

837
01:00:13,529 --> 01:00:16,680
What are you talking about?
Aren't we going to a party?

838
01:00:16,849 --> 01:00:21,161
Sure we are. But I just want to stop by
my theatre first for a couple of minutes.

839
01:00:21,329 --> 01:00:25,117
I have kind of a problem that I thought
maybe you could help me with.

840
01:00:25,289 --> 01:00:26,688
All right?

841
01:00:26,849 --> 01:00:30,683
Why, I suppose so.

842
01:00:30,849 --> 01:00:34,364
But won't Mr. Coudair wonder
where we are?

843
01:00:34,529 --> 01:00:37,601
I don't think so. No.

844
01:00:38,329 --> 01:00:40,684
Beauty like hers demands things,
Mr. McGuire:

845
01:00:40,849 --> 01:00:43,568
Luxury, gentle living, money.

846
01:00:43,729 --> 01:00:46,004
- I have these.
- Are you sure she wants them?

847
01:00:46,169 --> 01:00:48,080
What beautiful young girl doesn't?

848
01:00:48,249 --> 01:00:51,161
Have you given her the chance
to make up her own mind?

849
01:00:51,329 --> 01:00:53,524
Have you?

850
01:00:54,929 --> 01:00:58,478
That's fair enough.
Why don't we leave it up to her?

851
01:00:58,649 --> 01:01:00,879
She won't leave you.
She's in love with you.

852
01:01:01,049 --> 01:01:03,165
- I'm in love with her.
- I doubt that.

853
01:01:03,329 --> 01:01:06,366
If you were, you wouldn't let her
remain in obscurity.

854
01:01:06,529 --> 01:01:10,647
Don't you think I'd make her go
if I thought she'd be happier with...?

855
01:01:11,329 --> 01:01:13,889
No, Mr. Coudair, I don't believe
she would be.

856
01:01:14,049 --> 01:01:16,882
I don't believe it for a minute. L...

857
01:01:22,929 --> 01:01:24,157
Beautiful, isn't she?

858
01:01:24,369 --> 01:01:25,643
Yes.

859
01:01:26,449 --> 01:01:29,043
I've never seen that picture before.
Is it new?

860
01:01:29,529 --> 01:01:32,487
That is a picture of Rusty's
grandmother, Mr. McGuire.

861
01:01:32,649 --> 01:01:35,686
- I was very much in love with her.
- Well, I'll be darned.

862
01:01:35,849 --> 01:01:39,080
That's exactly what I said to myself
when I first saw Rusty.

863
01:01:39,249 --> 01:01:41,683
Amazing resemblance, isn't there?

864
01:01:41,849 --> 01:01:44,761
She was a dancer too,
worked at Tony Pastor's.

865
01:01:44,929 --> 01:01:46,408
Tony Pastor's, huh?

866
01:01:46,569 --> 01:01:48,161
It was wrong for her...

867
01:01:48,329 --> 01:01:51,082
...as Danny McGuire's is wrong
for her granddaughter.

868
01:01:51,249 --> 01:01:53,080
You decided that right away, huh?

869
01:01:53,249 --> 01:01:55,285
Yes, so I asked her to marry me.

870
01:01:55,449 --> 01:01:57,565
Did she?

871
01:01:57,729 --> 01:02:00,038
Sit down, won't you?

872
01:02:00,729 --> 01:02:04,244
I'll never forget the day I asked her up
here to meet my mother.

873
01:02:04,529 --> 01:02:08,078
My mother was society,
and Maribelle a girl from the stage.

874
01:02:08,249 --> 01:02:11,685
Maribelle stood there with her chin up
and her knees shaking...

875
01:02:11,849 --> 01:02:15,080
...and Mother was looking
her over very thoroughly.

876
01:02:15,249 --> 01:02:20,118
Mother just shook her head
and said, "Poor John."

877
01:02:20,849 --> 01:02:24,205
I don't suppose you remember
a song called "Poor John."

878
01:02:24,369 --> 01:02:25,882
That's how she punished me...

879
01:02:26,049 --> 01:02:30,486
...by singing it until everyone
in New York knew that I was "Poor John."

880
01:02:30,649 --> 01:02:32,002
Let me tell you about one night.

881
01:02:51,009 --> 01:02:54,046
<i>I ought to think myself a lucky girl</i>

882
01:02:54,209 --> 01:02:55,847
<i>I know</i>

883
01:02:56,009 --> 01:02:58,887
<i>'Cause I'm engaged</i>
<i>But still somehow</i>

884
01:02:59,049 --> 01:03:01,961
<i>I don't think so</i>

885
